45:30.099 --> 45:32.802
<i>who was in the pilot,
said how much she liked Rhoda?"</i>

45:32.802 --> 45:34.103
♪ (INSPIRING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

45:34.103 --> 45:36.404
BROOKS:
<i>That and cutting the script</i>

45:36.404 --> 45:39.440
<i>turned the bomb into the pilot
that people talk about.</i>

45:39.440 --> 45:44.349
♪ ("MARY TYLER MOORE SHOW"
THEME SONG PLAYING) ♪

45:47.952 --> 45:53.292
<i>♪ How will you make it
On your own ♪</i>

45:55.092 --> 45:58.226
<i>♪ This world is awfully big ♪</i>

45:58.226 --> 46:01.624
<i>♪ Girl, this time
You're all alone ♪</i>

46:01.624 --> 46:05.500
<i>♪ But it's time
You started living ♪</i>

46:05.500 --> 46:09.238
<i>♪ It's time you let someone else
Do some giving ♪</i>

46:09.238 --> 46:13.008
<i>♪ Love is all around
No need to waste it ♪</i>

46:13.008 --> 46:17.079
<i>♪ You can have the town
Why don't you take it? ♪</i>

46:17.079 --> 46:23.288
<i>♪ You might just make it
After all ♪</i>

46:24.354 --> 46:31.354
<i>♪ You might just make it
After all ♪</i>

46:31.595 --> 46:34.957
- ♪ (THEME MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
- ♪ (JOLLY MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

46:34.957 --> 46:37.232
ROSIE O'DONNELL: <i>I was eight
when the first episode came on</i>

46:37.232 --> 46:39.934
<i>and I hadn't seen one
where a woman,</i>

46:39.934 --> 46:43.171
<i>especially a single woman
without a man to depend on,</i>

46:43.171 --> 46:47.810
<i>was making her own way in life.
It seared into my brain.</i>

46:47.810 --> 46:49.572
Look, miss, would you try

46:49.572 --> 46:51.450
answering the questions
as I ask 'em?

46:52.550 --> 46:53.716
Yes, Mr. Grant, I will.

46:53.716 --> 46:55.150
But it does seem
that you've been asking

46:55.150 --> 46:57.720
a lot of very personal questions
that don't have a thing to do

46:57.720 --> 47:00.155
with my qualifications
for this job.

47:00.155 --> 47:01.757
JULIA LOUIS-DREYFUS:
<i>There was no other show</i>

47:01.757 --> 47:03.224
<i>like</i> The Mary Tyler Moore Show.

47:03.224 --> 47:07.990
<i>Her morphing from Laura Petrie
into Mary Richards</i>

47:07.990 --> 47:14.435
<i>was such a feminist statement
and one that got into my bones.</i>

47:14.435 --> 47:17.105
KATIE COURIC:
<i>Watching this incredible woman</i>

47:17.105 --> 47:20.475
<i>who was strong and funny,
and independent,</i>

47:20.475 --> 47:24.046
<i>then gets her own apartment
with the wooden "M" on the wall.</i>

47:24.046 --> 47:26.716
- So you're, uh, Rhoda?
- Morgenstern.

47:26.716 --> 47:28.283
Ah! And I'm Mary Richards.

47:28.283 --> 47:31.223
Oh, hello. (CHUCKLES)
Get outta my apartment!

47:32.523 --> 47:36.759
KATIE: <i>She had funny neighbors
like Rhoda and Phyllis.</i>

47:36.759 --> 47:39.689
But Mary,
it's your duty as a woman

47:39.689 --> 47:41.597
to take whatever
you could get... (SNIFFS)

47:41.597 --> 47:42.998
...whether you want it or not.

47:42.998 --> 47:46.134
KATIE: <i>And a great crew
of people with whom she worked.</i>

47:46.134 --> 47:48.170
I'd tell you to stop reading
over my shoulder

47:48.170 --> 47:50.409
but you need all the practice
you can get.

47:52.076 --> 47:53.809
- Hi.
- You're late, Mar.

47:53.809 --> 47:55.004
I know.

47:55.004 --> 47:57.179
KATIE: <i>It opened my eyes to,
"Wow, I wanna do that too."</i>

47:57.179 --> 48:00.449
A beautiful romance
just blew up in her face.

48:00.449 --> 48:03.385
It did not blow up.
I made the decision.

48:03.385 --> 48:04.787
♪ (SOLEMN
PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

48:04.787 --> 48:06.388
JULIA: <i>It wasn't
just Mary Richards</i>

48:06.388 --> 48:12.628
<i>who was this extraordinarily
single ambitious career woman.</i>

48:12.628 --> 48:13.723
<i>She was surrounded</i>

48:13.723 --> 48:17.132
<i>by very strong
comedic female characters.</i>

48:17.132 --> 48:18.467
- Yeah, I--
- You're talking

48:18.467 --> 48:21.536
about Midwestern love,
I'm talking about Bronx love.

48:21.536 --> 48:25.340
There's a certain amount
of guilt that goes with that.

48:25.340 --> 48:28.076
MARY: <i>Part of being
a successful artist</i>

48:28.076 --> 48:31.146
<i>is being open to new ideas
and input.</i>

48:31.146 --> 48:33.114
TREVA:
<i>She was a big, big supporter</i>

48:33.114 --> 48:35.450
<i>of what the pilot
said about her.</i>

48:35.450 --> 48:39.921
<i>She was on the side
of risk-taking.</i>

48:39.921 --> 48:41.490
- Divorced?
- MARY: No.

48:41.490 --> 48:42.825
- Never married.
- No.

48:42.825 --> 48:44.427
- ED: Why?
- Why?

48:44.427 --> 48:46.161
Hmm. Your type?

48:46.161 --> 48:49.498
Mr. Grant, there's no
simple answer to that question.

48:49.498 --> 48:52.367
MARY: <i>There had been some shows
about single women before</i>

48:52.367 --> 48:55.303
<i>but as in the case
of</i> The Marlo Thomas Show,

48:55.303 --> 48:57.405
<i>boy, it was
about getting married,</i>

48:57.405 --> 48:59.474
<i>and Jim and Allen
didn't wanna do that.</i>

48:59.474 --> 49:02.878
<i>They wanted to show a woman
enjoying her life and her career</i>

49:02.878 --> 49:04.349
<i>and meeting these challenges.</i>

49:05.515 --> 49:07.415
BROOKS: <i>They each
had a great backbone.</i>

49:07.415 --> 49:09.151
- (DOORBELL BUZZES)
- BROOKS: The character and Mary

49:09.151 --> 49:11.452
<i>had a great backbone
that was real.</i>

49:11.452 --> 49:13.188
<i>You know,
that kind of substance,</i>

49:13.188 --> 49:14.923
<i>intrinsic dignity of being</i>

49:14.923 --> 49:17.026
<i>and of other people's dignity
of being.</i>

49:17.026 --> 49:19.561
<i>So, in a way,
you're describing class.</i>

49:19.561 --> 49:23.468
Uh. Mary, Uh, uh. Did--
Did you just say goodbye?

49:25.670 --> 49:26.568
Uh-huh.

49:26.568 --> 49:29.008
(CHUCKLES)
That's what I thought you said.

49:30.775 --> 49:32.641
Take... take care of yourself.

49:32.641 --> 49:35.210
- ♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
- I think I just did.

49:35.210 --> 49:36.445
♪ (QUIRKY MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

49:36.445 --> 49:37.846
RONA:
You were kind of locked up.

49:37.846 --> 49:43.084
I mean, I say locked up in that
that the image on the screen

49:43.084 --> 49:46.922
in the series, certainly
never matched the real Mary.

49:46.922 --> 49:50.595
That's right. Right.
I was never single.

49:51.563 --> 49:54.129
Mary Richards. Hmm.

49:54.129 --> 49:56.732
It is still Richards, isn't it?

49:56.732 --> 50:00.305
Uh. Yes.
It's, uh, still Mary too.

50:01.867 --> 50:04.173
So, you've never been married,
Mary?

50:04.173 --> 50:06.074
- No, Estelle, I haven't.
- Hmm.

50:06.074 --> 50:07.409
I've been married twice.

50:07.409 --> 50:09.714
She liked it so much
the first time.

50:12.049 --> 50:13.482
I think you can look
at a show like ours

50:13.482 --> 50:15.918
and look at some
of the relationships

50:15.918 --> 50:19.458
and say to yourself
after you've laughed...

50:20.691 --> 50:23.726
"Son of a gun.
That happened to me once."

50:23.726 --> 50:24.960
♪ (LIGHTHEARTED MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

50:24.960 --> 50:26.696
BROOKS: <i>There's no way
we can deal</i>

50:26.696 --> 50:29.097
<i>with how humbling luck is.</i>

50:29.097 --> 50:30.633
<i>- They programmed us...</i>
- (MARY YELPS)

50:30.633 --> 50:31.833
<i>...in a death time slot</i>

50:31.833 --> 50:35.637
<i>because whoever was in charge
of CBS then, didn't like us.</i>

50:35.637 --> 50:38.006
<i>Where we were in mourning
when we learned about it,</i>

50:38.006 --> 50:39.508
<i>it meant they were eating us up.</i>

50:39.508 --> 50:41.476
<i>They were just
throwing away the shows.</i>

50:41.476 --> 50:43.912
<i>The president of the company,
the businessman,</i>

50:43.912 --> 50:45.815
<i>he was promoted
from head of sales</i>

50:45.815 --> 50:47.750
<i>to head of the network.</i>

50:47.750 --> 50:48.884
<i>First thing he did</i>

50:48.884 --> 50:51.020
<i>was all those
situation comedy shows</i>

50:51.020 --> 50:53.055
<i>that had ruled the airways, canceled,</i>

50:53.055 --> 50:55.323
<i>lots of top ten shows.</i>

50:55.323 --> 50:57.826
<i>And then he put</i>
All in the Family <i>on the air</i>

50:57.826 --> 51:01.329
<i>and gave us the best time period
he had and saved us.</i>

51:01.329 --> 51:02.630
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

51:02.630 --> 51:05.033
Hi, I'm Mary Tyler Moore
and I just want you to know

51:05.033 --> 51:06.101
that starting this fall,

51:06.101 --> 51:07.936
Bob Newhart and I
will be back-to-back

51:07.936 --> 51:09.471
every Saturday night on CBS.

51:09.471 --> 51:11.807
Why do you fight it?
The world's changing.

51:11.807 --> 51:13.074
ROB: <i>They were on the same night</i>

51:13.074 --> 51:14.309
<i>we were on for</i>
All in the Family.

51:14.309 --> 51:16.711
<i>It was M*A*S*H.
And then Bob Newhart</i>

51:16.711 --> 51:18.647
<i>and Mary Tyler Moore,
and then Carol Barnett,</i>

51:18.647 --> 51:19.943
<i>we had a great lineup.</i>

51:19.943 --> 51:22.017
ROSIE: <i>You had to wait
until it was on.</i>

51:22.017 --> 51:23.051
(CHUCKLES) <i>Y'know?</i>

51:23.051 --> 51:25.287
<i>And if you missed it,
you missed it.</i>

51:25.287 --> 51:27.589
<i>- It was appointment TV for me.</i>
- ♪ (GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

51:27.589 --> 51:31.160
RONDA RICH TINKER: <i>I would lie
on the floor, on my stomach</i>

51:31.160 --> 51:32.660
<i>right in front of the TV.</i>

51:32.660 --> 51:34.930
DEBRA MARTIN CHASE:
<i>My mother and I would watch</i>

51:34.930 --> 51:36.164
<i>Mary Tyler Moore together.</i>

51:36.164 --> 51:37.832
DEBRA: <i>Mary spoke to all of us.</i>

51:37.832 --> 51:42.570
<i>Women could be independent,
could have careers,</i>

51:42.570 --> 51:44.540
<i>could stand
on their own two feet</i>

51:44.540 --> 51:45.741
<i>without a man.</i>

51:45.741 --> 51:47.442
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

51:47.442 --> 51:51.647
KATIE: <i>I just remember
it being part of my routine</i>

51:51.647 --> 51:53.481
<i>on the weekends.</i>

51:53.481 --> 51:57.285
BROOKS: <i>We had an audience
right away and we kept it.</i>

51:57.285 --> 52:01.056
<i>And that was when everybody
stayed home and watched.</i>

52:01.056 --> 52:02.457
<i>Grant Tinker used to say,</i>

52:02.457 --> 52:04.159
<i>"You could fly across
the United States,</i>

52:04.159 --> 52:06.094
<i>jump out of a plane
and very likely land</i>

52:06.094 --> 52:08.730
<i>on somebody watching your show."</i>

52:08.730 --> 52:13.435
JOEL GREY: <i>If you transcend
all of the expectations,</i>

52:13.435 --> 52:14.902
- changes everything.
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

52:14.902 --> 52:21.209
JOEL: <i>I'm sure her expectations
of her life changed after that,</i>

52:21.209 --> 52:25.480
<i>as did everyone else's
expectations of her.</i>

52:25.480 --> 52:26.714
- I need to get ready.
- Yeah, I hope.

52:26.714 --> 52:29.151
- Boy, I hate those meetings.
- You never used to.

52:29.151 --> 52:31.586
Yeah, well, it used to be I felt
I could be myself.

52:31.586 --> 52:35.556
Now, I feel
I represent women everywhere.

52:35.556 --> 52:39.427
JOHN: <i>Mary was so stellar
at being that center</i>

52:39.427 --> 52:41.096
<i>that held everything together.</i>

52:41.096 --> 52:43.699
<i>And she always wanted her folks
to be proud.</i>

52:43.699 --> 52:44.967
<i>They weren't effusive.</i>

52:44.967 --> 52:46.601
<i>I've often wondered
how much time</i>

52:46.601 --> 52:50.005
<i>was spent with Mary in her mind,
with her folks.</i>

52:50.005 --> 52:52.640
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

52:52.640 --> 52:54.777
MARY: (OVER MIC) Would you all
like to meet the producers

52:54.777 --> 52:55.939
of <i>Mary Tyler Moore?</i>

52:55.939 --> 52:59.280
- My mom and dad.
- (AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

52:59.280 --> 53:01.044
MARY: (OVER MIC)
And February 14th,

53:01.044 --> 53:03.351
they're celebrating
their 50th anniversary.

53:03.351 --> 53:06.291
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING, CHEERING)

53:08.892 --> 53:12.192
So, what's the secret
of 50 years, Mom and Dad?

53:13.297 --> 53:15.763
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING, APPLAUDING)

53:15.763 --> 53:18.233
- Lots of love and respect.
- MARY: (OVER MIC) That's right.

53:18.233 --> 53:19.534
I go along with that.

53:19.534 --> 53:21.603
MARY: (OVER MIC) <i>Okay, why not?
That's a smart way.</i>

53:21.603 --> 53:22.737
BETTY WHITE:
<i>You probably remember</i>

53:22.737 --> 53:25.273
<i>seeing this great cover
on</i> TV Guide.

53:25.273 --> 53:27.943
Well, right now, right here,
on <i>The Pet Set,</i>

53:27.943 --> 53:31.579
we have this very star
as our very special guest.

53:31.579 --> 53:33.982
I'd like you
to meet Dis William. (CHUCKLES)

53:33.982 --> 53:36.417
Oh, and he brought a girl
with him, Mary Tyler Moore.

53:36.417 --> 53:37.814
- (LAUGHS)
- Hello there. (CHUCKLES)

53:37.814 --> 53:40.255
- Hi.
- (AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

53:40.255 --> 53:42.591
I noticed on the set of,
of course,

53:42.591 --> 53:45.093
<i>The Mary Tyler Moore Show,</i>
very prominently displayed

53:45.093 --> 53:46.762
on the set is a picture
of these two.

53:46.762 --> 53:48.396
- Is that for luck?
- Yeah, it's for luck.

53:48.396 --> 53:49.698
And also
because the prop man said,

53:49.698 --> 53:52.067
"Do you have any pictures
of anybody in your family

53:52.067 --> 53:53.234
you'd like to have on the show?

53:53.234 --> 53:54.802
The set needs
a little warming up." (CHUCKLES)

53:54.802 --> 53:56.838
- (BETTY CHUCKLES)
- And I don't know
why I brought in pictures

53:56.838 --> 53:59.409
of the poodles
instead of my mother or father.

53:59.409 --> 54:00.575
Ow. (CLICKS TONGUE)

54:00.575 --> 54:03.745
- What happened?
- Nothing, I just cut myself.

54:03.745 --> 54:05.546
It's okay. It's just a...
it's just a tiny one.

54:05.546 --> 54:07.082
- Come on, let me look at it.
- No.

54:07.082 --> 54:09.584
- ♪ (SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
- When you were a little girl,

54:09.584 --> 54:11.420
you wouldn't let me look
when you cut yourself.

54:11.420 --> 54:13.288
I was always afraid
you'd stitch it up.

54:13.288 --> 54:16.458
JOHN: <i>There was a scene
where her father</i>

54:16.458 --> 54:18.593
<i>tells her how much
he cares for her.</i>

54:18.593 --> 54:20.728
<i>Mary just wanted
to get it right.</i>

54:20.728 --> 54:24.561
You don't cry when you...
cut your finger anymore?

54:24.561 --> 54:25.737
No. (SCOFFS)

54:27.404 --> 54:28.840
What does make you cry?

54:30.274 --> 54:33.374
Oh, mostly dumb things.
(CHUCKLES)

54:33.374 --> 54:34.943
JOHN:
<i>And I remember being there</i>

54:34.943 --> 54:37.513
<i>and I don't know that
that was very easy for her.</i>

54:37.513 --> 54:39.181
I keep a few in here.

54:39.181 --> 54:41.150
JOHN: <i>That scene
even then moved me</i>

54:41.150 --> 54:42.717
<i>because when her folks
would come over</i>

54:42.717 --> 54:46.654
<i>on the rare occasion for dinner,
it was always a little,</i>

54:46.654 --> 54:48.791
<i>you're just waiting
for something to happen.</i>

54:48.791 --> 54:51.291
<i>Something that would
light the fuse.</i>

54:52.231 --> 54:53.465
Mary...

54:55.266 --> 54:56.535
are you ever lonely?

54:58.502 --> 55:00.439
No. Not too often, Daddy.

55:01.539 --> 55:02.874
I have a good life.

55:03.408 --> 55:04.576
I'm glad...

55:06.177 --> 55:08.480
because... (SIGHS)

55:09.513 --> 55:11.650
...I'm sorry
about your graduation,

55:12.517 --> 55:14.353
anything else I missed.

55:16.287 --> 55:17.556
I love you, baby.

55:20.690 --> 55:25.530
(SNIFFS) Well, it isn't always
dumb things that make me cry.

55:27.932 --> 55:29.425
(SIGHS) There. That...

55:29.425 --> 55:33.201
That should be all right.
Careful how you handle knives.

55:33.201 --> 55:34.537
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

55:34.537 --> 55:36.933
- Hey, Daddy? (SNIFFLES)
- Mm-hmm?

55:36.933 --> 55:38.907
You bandaged the wrong finger.

55:38.907 --> 55:41.676
- (CHUCKLES)
- ♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

55:41.676 --> 55:43.378
INTERVIEWER: Why do you think
it's such a winner,

55:43.378 --> 55:45.746
<i>The Mary Tyler Moore Show?</i>

55:45.746 --> 55:49.417
I think because of the casting,
primarily me.

55:49.417 --> 55:50.886
- No. (CHUCKLES)
- (INTERVIEWER LAUGHS)

55:50.886 --> 55:54.256
No, but it really
is an extraordinary cast.

55:54.256 --> 55:56.028
And I think
because of the writing.

55:58.262 --> 55:59.494
SUSAN SILVER:
The Mary Tyler Moore Show

55:59.494 --> 56:01.496
<i>hired the most women
of any show.</i>

56:01.496 --> 56:05.733
<i>And it changed
the language of television.</i>

56:05.733 --> 56:08.504
TREVA: <i>It was wonderful
of Jim and Allen.</i>

56:08.504 --> 56:09.737
<i>They really wanted to...</i>

56:09.737 --> 56:11.974
(CHUCKLES) <i>...get it
from the horse's mouth.</i>

56:11.974 --> 56:13.575
BROOKS: <i>It didn't seem
like we were having</i>

56:13.575 --> 56:15.405
<i>a eureka moment when we said,</i>

56:15.405 --> 56:18.146
(CHUCKLES) <i>"Women would be good
to write on this show</i>

56:18.146 --> 56:19.581
<i>about these women."</i>

56:19.581 --> 56:22.952
<i>Totally logical thought pattern.
It was the right thing to do.</i>

56:22.952 --> 56:23.919
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

56:23.919 --> 56:25.988
MARY: <i>Jim said,
"I can write a lot of stuff.</i>

56:25.988 --> 56:27.622
<i>I'm very seldom stumped</i>

56:27.622 --> 56:30.425
<i>but you've got stuff
in your purse</i>

56:30.425 --> 56:32.594
<i>that I don't know anything about</i>

56:32.594 --> 56:35.296
<i>and that's what I want you
to empty out for me.</i>

56:35.296 --> 56:37.599
<i>I wanna know what women know."</i>

56:37.599 --> 56:39.334
SUSAN: <i>And I said,
I was the last person</i>

56:39.334 --> 56:40.503
<i>to get a bra. I love it.</i>

56:40.503 --> 56:41.803
<i>I'm not burning it</i>

56:41.803 --> 56:43.972
<i>but I will make
a contribution to feminism</i>

56:43.972 --> 56:46.341
<i>by having my own career
and being a feminist,</i>

56:46.341 --> 56:48.710
<i>but not by marching.</i>

56:48.710 --> 56:51.479
<i>Women speak differently,
and we have different ideas</i>

56:51.479 --> 56:52.881
<i>and we have different stories.</i>

56:52.881 --> 56:56.318
<i>I'm sure a man has never had
to wear a bad bridesmaid dress.</i>

56:56.318 --> 56:59.058
- Mary.
- MARY: Yeah?

57:00.920 --> 57:02.624
Oh, it's bad, huh?

57:02.624 --> 57:05.730
Well, come on out, kid.
How bad could it be?

57:13.505 --> 57:14.839
That bad, huh?

57:16.374 --> 57:19.475
I'd say, uh,
about the only thing worse

57:19.475 --> 57:21.076
than this dress...

57:21.076 --> 57:24.746
- would be this dress in purple.
- In purple.

57:24.746 --> 57:26.447
SUSAN:
<i>Mary Tyler Moore was real.</i>

57:26.447 --> 57:27.682
<i>And it was the way real women</i>

57:27.682 --> 57:29.551
<i>talked to their parents
and their dates,</i>

57:29.551 --> 57:32.754
<i>and their girlfriends,
and Mary was the example.</i>

57:32.754 --> 57:35.190
<i>A Chicago guy had written
an article saying,</i>

57:35.190 --> 57:37.793
<i>"Mary doesn't have enough sex."
So I went in, and I said,</i>

57:37.793 --> 57:40.128
<i>"I have a show
where she can have sex."</i>

57:40.128 --> 57:41.862
- MARY: Rhoda?
- What?

57:41.862 --> 57:45.067
- Do you think I'm under-sexed?
- (SIGHS) I hope so.

57:45.067 --> 57:46.501
Really. I'd like to think

57:46.501 --> 57:48.540
there's one thing I'm better at
than you are.

57:49.606 --> 57:51.073
SUSAN: <i>All those things
we were learning</i>

57:51.073 --> 57:52.741
<i>were okay to talk about</i>

57:52.741 --> 57:54.775
<i>and to do at the same time
that the show did them.</i>

57:54.775 --> 57:57.579
<i>But it changed the way
women saw themselves.</i>

57:57.579 --> 58:00.148
- Have a nice time, you two.
- You too, Mom.

58:00.148 --> 58:01.517
Don't forget to take your pill.

58:01.517 --> 58:02.821
- I won't.
- I won't.

58:06.891 --> 58:08.256
BROOKS: <i>It was a throwaway joke</i>

58:08.256 --> 58:12.060
<i>and...</i> (CHUCKLES) <i>...it was racy
at the time and it was huge.</i>

58:12.060 --> 58:13.662
I call it creeping smut.

58:13.662 --> 58:16.364
I see it everywhere,
in bookstores, in movies,

58:16.364 --> 58:17.966
in libraries,
and now in television.

58:17.966 --> 58:18.834
Look what happened

58:18.834 --> 58:20.169
<i>on The Mary Tyler Moore Show</i> recently.

58:20.169 --> 58:23.405
She went out on a date
and she stayed out all night.

58:23.405 --> 58:26.576
BEA ARTHUR: All night?
Our little Mary?

58:26.576 --> 58:28.610
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

58:28.610 --> 58:30.145
You can sneer
if you want, Maude.

58:30.145 --> 58:31.080
But let me tell you this,

58:31.080 --> 58:33.818
as Mary Tyler Moore goes,
so goes America.

58:34.718 --> 58:36.956
Look, I'm not sure
if this fits right.

58:38.956 --> 58:40.823
NORMAN LEAR:
<i>Mary Tyler Moore for television</i>

58:40.823 --> 58:43.891
<i>represented America
at that moment</i>

58:43.891 --> 58:48.596
<i>in that fresh release
from the ancient womanhood.</i>

58:48.596 --> 58:51.299
In a landmark ruling,
the Supreme Court today,

58:51.299 --> 58:53.569
- legalized abortions.
- ♪ (UPLIFTING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

58:53.569 --> 58:55.870
- Murray, your marriage?
- Mary,

58:55.870 --> 59:00.042
you know I love Marie.
Marie is not Gloria Steinem.

59:00.042 --> 59:03.212
Well, what's this
"Gloria Steinem" thing you have?

59:03.212 --> 59:05.880
I mean, you take away
Gloria Steinem's super intellect

59:05.880 --> 59:09.154
and what do you got? (CHUCKLES)
Never mind, bad example.

59:10.354 --> 59:12.320
(HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING)

59:12.320 --> 59:13.656
BROOKS: <i>I was asked to speak</i>

59:13.656 --> 59:15.590
<i>to Lady Bird Johnson's</i>

59:15.590 --> 59:17.725
<i>- conference of women...</i>
- (BIRDS CHIRPING)

59:17.725 --> 59:21.563
<i>...and it was a theater
holding 1200 people, all women.</i>

59:21.563 --> 59:24.900
<i>And Gloria Steinem
spoke just before me,</i>

59:24.900 --> 59:26.901
<i>and derided</i>
The Mary Tyler Moore Show

59:26.901 --> 59:28.937
<i>- and that we're anti-feminist.</i>
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

59:28.937 --> 59:30.739
GLORIA: <i>The question is,
"Why does Mary Tyler Moore</i>

59:30.739 --> 59:32.941
<i>still call Mr. Grant,
'Mr. Grant?'"</i>

59:32.941 --> 59:35.277
BROOKS: <i>This comes up
every once in a while...</i>

59:35.277 --> 59:36.578
GLORIA: (LAUGHS) Oh, yeah?

59:36.578 --> 59:38.446
<i>...and it just...
it just seems right.</i>

59:38.446 --> 59:40.448
<i>We talk about doing a show--</i>

59:40.448 --> 59:41.950
- (CROWD BOOING)
- BROOKS: <i>No, no.</i>

59:41.950 --> 59:43.618
<i>And they booed me.</i> (CHUCKLES)

59:43.618 --> 59:47.156
(GLORIA LAUGHS,
SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)

59:47.156 --> 59:49.390
BROOKS: <i>Just based
on what seems right to us</i>

59:49.390 --> 59:50.893
<i>about the character's behavior.</i>

59:50.893 --> 59:52.727
- Mr. Grant, you should--
- Now, it won't work

59:52.727 --> 59:55.667
if you're calling me
"Mr. Grant." Call me "Lou."

59:56.933 --> 01:00:00.063
Well, wait, uh, would that be
for, uh... just for the purpose

01:00:00.063 --> 01:00:01.937
of this conversation?

01:00:01.937 --> 01:00:03.875
We, uh... for,
you know, all time?

01:00:05.544 --> 01:00:06.711
I'll decide later.

01:00:08.446 --> 01:00:14.015
- You think you can, Mary?
- Call you not Mr. Grant? Sure.

01:00:14.015 --> 01:00:18.690
- Well, I'm glad it's okay.
- Oh, yes, it's okay to say it.

01:00:20.992 --> 01:00:25.364
- Really, Mary?
- Really, Lou.

01:00:27.431 --> 01:00:29.364
♪ (MELODIOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

01:00:29.364 --> 01:00:33.034
- Call me Mr. Grant.
- Thank you.

01:00:33.034 --> 01:00:35.604
Was there some talk one time
about the <i>Mary Tyler Moore Show</i>

01:00:35.604 --> 01:00:37.906
being anti-women's lib or...

01:00:37.906 --> 01:00:39.741
- or too pro-women's lib...
- Oh, well, it depends...

01:00:39.741 --> 01:00:41.404
- ...or something.
- ...on where you're sitting.

01:00:41.404 --> 01:00:42.844
I... I don't think
it's anti at all.

01:00:42.844 --> 01:00:45.881
I think there are two ladies,
living by themselves, working.

01:00:45.881 --> 01:00:48.378
Very-- As realistically
as you can get

01:00:48.378 --> 01:00:49.612
on a television series
at the time.

01:00:49.612 --> 01:00:51.086
But the viewers see it
in those terms sometimes.

01:00:51.086 --> 01:00:54.556
Sh-- Oh, yeah,
you see what you feel, you know?

01:00:54.556 --> 01:00:55.657
But do you ever find yourself

01:00:55.657 --> 01:00:57.726
pandering to the people
who are your fans

01:00:57.726 --> 01:00:59.255
so that you can keep them
your fans?

01:00:59.255 --> 01:01:00.595
- No.
- INTERVIEWER: Anyway...

01:01:00.595 --> 01:01:02.664
- No, not at all.
- ...in any way? Get around?

01:01:02.664 --> 01:01:05.167
See, there is a perfectly
logical explanation

01:01:05.167 --> 01:01:06.001
for what you heard.

01:01:06.001 --> 01:01:08.007
Oh, really, Mary?
And what is it?

01:01:09.740 --> 01:01:11.272
We were having an orgy.

01:01:11.272 --> 01:01:13.536
JIM: <i>If you wanna do a show
on network television,</i>

01:01:13.536 --> 01:01:16.178
<i>you have to appeal
to the whole country.</i>

01:01:16.178 --> 01:01:19.747
<i>You had to appease
40 million people.</i>

01:01:19.747 --> 01:01:23.984
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

01:01:23.984 --> 01:01:28.156
RONDA: <i>Mary was what I like
to call a feminine feminist.</i>

01:01:28.156 --> 01:01:32.927
<i>I know she didn't like
to call herself a feminist.</i>

01:01:32.927 --> 01:01:36.264
BEVERLY: <i>She didn't think
feminism was so hotsy-totsy.</i>

01:01:36.264 --> 01:01:39.201
<i>There were women
that just didn't like it.</i>

01:01:39.201 --> 01:01:42.204
<i>She identified with it
up to a point.</i>

01:01:42.204 --> 01:01:46.308
RONDA: <i>She loved the spoils
of femininity.</i>

01:01:46.308 --> 01:01:50.911
<i>She loved the clothes, the hair
and the makeup,</i>

01:01:50.911 --> 01:01:55.551
<i>and she loved to take that
and dress up how tough she was.</i>

01:01:55.551 --> 01:01:57.252
<i>It was a good costume for her.</i>

01:01:57.252 --> 01:01:59.955
BEVERLY: <i>One day I said,
"You are a woman's libber.</i>

01:01:59.955 --> 01:02:01.824
<i>You have your own show.</i>

01:02:01.824 --> 01:02:05.227
<i>You have a child
and you were divorced.</i>

01:02:05.227 --> 01:02:08.464
<i>You have set the standard
for a woman</i>

01:02:08.464 --> 01:02:10.966
<i>to be on her own."</i>

01:02:10.966 --> 01:02:13.502
JIM: <i>She was aloof.
She was reserved.</i>

01:02:13.502 --> 01:02:14.970
<i>She had an incredible veneer.</i>

01:02:14.970 --> 01:02:18.777
<i>I only saw power from her.
I didn't see underneath.</i>

01:02:19.643 --> 01:02:22.310
JOHN:
<i>Mary was either fully engaged</i>

01:02:22.310 --> 01:02:26.782
<i>in the activity around her
and giving you her attention</i>

01:02:26.782 --> 01:02:29.852
<i>or she was completely disengaged,</i>

01:02:29.852 --> 01:02:33.255
<i>virtually in thought
all the time.</i>

01:02:33.255 --> 01:02:35.623
BEVERLY:
<i>She always wanted to be better.</i>

01:02:35.623 --> 01:02:38.727
<i>She always wanted
to be different.</i>

01:02:38.727 --> 01:02:40.328
<i>I just thought she was marvelous</i>

01:02:40.328 --> 01:02:42.297
<i>and every time
she would be insecure and say,</i>

01:02:42.297 --> 01:02:45.901
<i>"I'm so worried. I mean,
I have to be really good."</i>

01:02:45.901 --> 01:02:48.504
The Sunday show,
Mary Richards, producer.

01:02:48.504 --> 01:02:50.071
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS, CHEERS)

01:02:50.071 --> 01:02:52.975
BEVERLY: <i>Who was Mary
really in real life?</i>

01:02:52.975 --> 01:02:56.348
<i>She was insecure
about buying lipstick.</i>

01:02:57.749 --> 01:02:59.181
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

01:02:59.181 --> 01:03:02.618
I usually look
so much better than this.

01:03:02.618 --> 01:03:04.123
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

01:03:06.323 --> 01:03:09.090
JOHN: <i>I have this image
of Mary walking.</i>

01:03:09.090 --> 01:03:11.559
<i>It's evident in the main title
of her show.</i>

01:03:11.559 --> 01:03:15.364
<i>She looks proud and almost regal
and she wasn't that way at all.</i>

01:03:15.364 --> 01:03:17.999
<i>It just was
how she carried herself.</i>

01:03:17.999 --> 01:03:20.535
ED: <i>There's the actress Mary</i>

01:03:20.535 --> 01:03:24.773
<i>who was the best civilian
in charge I've ever seen.</i>

01:03:24.773 --> 01:03:26.607
<i>She was cold-blooded in her way.</i>

01:03:26.607 --> 01:03:30.582
<i>And there's the character Mary
who was an adorable doll.</i>

01:03:32.550 --> 01:03:35.084
There's not a great deal
of control in acting.

01:03:35.084 --> 01:03:36.686
RONA: Did you have
a lot of control over

01:03:36.686 --> 01:03:37.953
MTM Enterprises?

01:03:37.953 --> 01:03:39.855
No, I was never
involved in that.

01:03:39.855 --> 01:03:41.424
- Nor am I.
- RONA: It just bore your name?

01:03:41.424 --> 01:03:42.557
Yes.

01:03:42.557 --> 01:03:45.928
JIM: <i>MTM is Mary's company.
People don't realize that.</i>

01:03:45.928 --> 01:03:48.330
(SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)
That's all, folks.

01:03:48.330 --> 01:03:50.732
JOHN: <i>The portrait
that hangs in Mary's house,</i>

01:03:50.732 --> 01:03:52.835
<i>that was in my father's office.</i>

01:03:52.835 --> 01:03:55.003
<i>It was always clear
who the boss was.</i>

01:03:55.003 --> 01:03:57.438
<i>She was of course
the figurehead.</i>

01:03:57.438 --> 01:04:00.308
<i>But running the day-to-day,
my father was always</i>

01:04:00.308 --> 01:04:02.877
<i>at his post,
as he would call it.</i>

01:04:02.877 --> 01:04:05.975
<i>At that desk was the happiest
I'd ever seen him.</i>

01:04:05.975 --> 01:04:09.685
<i>That was his business to run.
And she was fine with that.</i>

01:04:09.685 --> 01:04:11.286
If Grant had come to me
and asked

01:04:11.286 --> 01:04:14.523
my feelings about something
opinion of, people or script,

01:04:14.523 --> 01:04:15.724
I would certainly give them.

01:04:15.724 --> 01:04:18.754
JOHN: <i>While they may have
talked about it, I don't know</i>

01:04:18.754 --> 01:04:21.329
<i>how much he would've
solicited her advice.</i>

01:04:21.329 --> 01:04:24.066
<i>I think they had lanes
in which they both stayed,</i>

01:04:24.066 --> 01:04:25.337
<i>and it worked out well.</i>

01:04:27.204 --> 01:04:31.106
The lead actress of the year
in a series is...

01:04:31.106 --> 01:04:34.413
- Mary Tyler Moore.
- (AUDIENCE CHEERS, APPLAUDS)

01:04:35.113 --> 01:04:36.311
JOAN: <i>I never saw Mary</i>

01:04:36.311 --> 01:04:39.014
<i>actively involved
in the business side of MTM,</i>

01:04:39.014 --> 01:04:41.784
<i>but there was no question
the company reflected</i>

01:04:41.784 --> 01:04:43.852
<i>her sensibilities.</i>

01:04:43.852 --> 01:04:45.921
<i>Mary was very instrumental,</i>

01:04:45.921 --> 01:04:48.651
<i>certainly in setting
the tone on set.</i>

01:04:48.651 --> 01:04:50.159
RONA: <i>Looking back,
do you regret</i>

01:04:50.159 --> 01:04:53.562
<i>that you didn't put
your own imprimatur on things?</i>

01:04:53.562 --> 01:04:56.564
MARY: <i>No. You know, one can be
guilty about the things</i>

01:04:56.564 --> 01:05:00.302
<i>one has never done in life.
I try not to do that.</i>

01:05:00.302 --> 01:05:02.570
<i>Sure. that would be nice
were I an entrepreneur</i>

01:05:02.570 --> 01:05:05.541
<i>and I had been involved
in that aspect of our business</i>

01:05:05.541 --> 01:05:07.242
<i>but it has never interested me.</i>

01:05:07.242 --> 01:05:10.112
<i>And nor has directing
or producing.</i>

01:05:10.112 --> 01:05:14.586
<i>And I really love acting
and that's all I want to do.</i>

01:05:15.519 --> 01:05:17.719
JAMES: <i>MTM became
a large company</i>

01:05:17.719 --> 01:05:19.387
<i>with a lot of shows on the air</i>

01:05:19.387 --> 01:05:21.456
<i>and a lot of different people
coming in.</i>

01:05:21.456 --> 01:05:23.792
JIM: <i>That was the west wing
of writing back then.</i>

01:05:23.792 --> 01:05:26.428
<i>- They had six sitcoms running.</i>
- (AUDIENCE CHEERS, APPLAUDS)

01:05:26.428 --> 01:05:28.730
JIM: <i>The network
would have a lot of notes</i>

01:05:28.730 --> 01:05:31.333
<i>and then Grant wouldn't
give them to the writers.</i>

01:05:31.333 --> 01:05:33.134
JAMES: <i>And the one thing
we all had in common</i>

01:05:33.134 --> 01:05:35.203
<i>was loving
the ass off Grant Tinker.</i>

01:05:35.203 --> 01:05:37.272
We're grateful to our cast,
you know that.

01:05:37.272 --> 01:05:39.474
We're grateful to Grant Tinker
for helping us

01:05:39.474 --> 01:05:41.544
to always preserve
our creative freedom.

01:05:41.544 --> 01:05:42.677
(AUDIENCE CHEERS, APPLAUDS)

01:05:42.677 --> 01:05:46.585
The winners are...
Ted Knight and Valerie Harper.

01:05:47.918 --> 01:05:50.919
VALERIE: <i>I do all my scenes
with Mary and she's the best.</i>

01:05:50.919 --> 01:05:54.089
She's a winner
and she lets us all win Emmys.

01:05:54.089 --> 01:05:55.594
I mean, it's incredible. Truly.

01:05:56.894 --> 01:05:58.889
JAMES: <i>Her modesty,
her humility,</i>

01:05:58.889 --> 01:06:01.362
<i>her need to have people
happy around her,</i>

01:06:01.362 --> 01:06:04.033
<i>created the tent
that went over all of us.</i>

01:06:04.033 --> 01:06:05.333
<i>Then don't make a mistake.</i>

01:06:05.333 --> 01:06:08.373
<i>No goody two shoes,
Mary wasn't goody two shoes.</i>

01:06:09.473 --> 01:06:11.343
<i>Nothing got in the way
of the work.</i>

01:06:13.644 --> 01:06:14.977
Thank you so very much.

01:06:14.977 --> 01:06:17.913
ED: I'd like to thank
our two producers,

01:06:17.913 --> 01:06:19.843
Alan Burns and Jim Brooks,

01:06:19.843 --> 01:06:22.483
for choosing me to be a member
of the best

01:06:22.483 --> 01:06:25.988
damn ensemble company
I've ever worked with.

01:06:25.988 --> 01:06:28.885
I really am so proud
to be in that company

01:06:28.885 --> 01:06:32.594
- and I am so grateful.
- Thank you very much.

01:06:32.594 --> 01:06:35.763
ED: Grant Tinker,
our godfather Jay Sandrich.

01:06:35.763 --> 01:06:39.034
- Most of all, we have Mary.
- ED: Treva Silverman.

01:06:39.034 --> 01:06:41.036
TREVA: <i>I was first woman
writing alone</i>

01:06:41.036 --> 01:06:42.437
<i>to win an Emmy.</i>

01:06:42.437 --> 01:06:44.573
I didn't know what it would
look like from here. (CHUCKLES)

01:06:44.573 --> 01:06:46.108
It looks terrific.

01:06:46.108 --> 01:06:49.973
Marty Cohen,
Susan Silver wrote those words,

01:06:49.973 --> 01:06:53.215
and without them,
I'd just be another pretty face.

01:06:53.215 --> 01:06:55.316
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

01:06:55.316 --> 01:06:57.218
JIM: <i>To be around that energy</i>

01:06:57.218 --> 01:06:59.520
<i>on the Radford lot
in Studio City,</i>

01:06:59.520 --> 01:07:01.122
<i>I'd like to say
it was the best of times.</i>

01:07:01.122 --> 01:07:03.325
<i>It was the best of times.
It was Camelot.</i>

01:07:03.325 --> 01:07:06.094
ED: Well, I would like to say
to actors everywhere,

01:07:06.094 --> 01:07:09.664
may you have the pleasure
and joy...

01:07:09.664 --> 01:07:14.469
of being with and working with
Mary Tyler Moore.

01:07:14.469 --> 01:07:17.973
- Thank you. Thank you all.
- (AUDIENCE CHEERS, APPLAUDS)

